o have advocated causes destined to lose in court but have had important, progressive long term effects on American society. He leads us through dramatic battles in American legal history, describing attempts by abolitionist lawyers to free fugitive slaves through the courts, Susan B. Anthony's trial for voting illegally, the post-Civil War challenges to segregation that resulted in the courts’ affirmation of the separate but equal doctrine in Plessy v. Ferguson, and Lobel’s own challenges to United States foreign policy during the 1980s and 1990s. Success Without Victory explores the political, social, and psychological contexts behind the cases themselves, as well as the eras from which they originated and the eras they subsequently influenced.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aJustice, Administration ofxPolitical aspects. 0aLawzUnited StatesvAnecdotes. 0aPolitical activistszUnited StatesvAnecdotes. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  aDefeat.  aactually.  aalways.  aauthor.  acases.  acourt.  aexclusive.  agains.  alegal.  alosing.  amutually.  apolitical.  aprovided.  ashows.  asome.  avictory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081475112140uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814752814.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814752814423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814752814/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA